06383nam a22007695i 9780824881016DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20192019hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248810167 a10.1515/97808248810162doi  a(DE-B1597)513331  a(OCoLC)1122562840  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBQ8512.9.C5bJ66 2019eb 7aREL0070102bisacsh04a294.3/92609512231 aJones, Charles B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChinese Pure Land Buddhism :bUnderstanding a Tradition of Practice /cCharles B. Jones; ed. by Richard K. Payne. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (222 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPure Land Buddhist Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editor's Preface -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. What Is the Chinese Pure Land Tradition? -- tChapter 3. The Development of the Concept of the Pure Land -- tChapter 4. Self-Power and Other-Power in Chinese Pure Land Buddhism -- tChapter 5. Ethics and Precepts in Chinese Pure Land Buddhism -- tChapter 6. Defending Pure Land in Late Imperial China -- tChapter 7. Methods of Nianfo in Chinese Pure Land Buddhism -- tChapter 8. Lushan Huiyuan -- tChapter 9. Conclusions -- tAppendix: The Thirteen Chinese Pure Land Patriarchs -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChinese Pure Land Buddhism: Understanding a Tradition of Practice is the first book in any western language to provide a comprehensive overview of Chinese Pure Land Buddhism. Even though Pure Land Buddhism was born in China and currently constitutes the dominant form of Buddhist practice there, it has previously received very little attention from western scholars. In this book, Charles B. Jones examines the reasons for the lack of scholarly attention and why the few past treatments of the topic missed many of its distinctive features. He argues that the Chinese Pure Land tradition, with its characteristic promise of rebirth in the Pure Land to even non-elite or undeserving practitioners, should not be viewed from the perspective of the Japanese Pure Land tradition, which differs greatly. More accurately contextualizing Chinese Pure Land Buddhism within the landscape of Chinese Buddhism and the broader global Buddhist tradition, this work celebrates Chinese Pure Land, not as a school or sect, but as a unique and inherently valuable "tradition of practice." This volume is organized thematically, clearly presenting topics such as the nature of the Pure Land, the relationship between "self-power" and "other-power," the practice of nianfo (buddha-recollection), and the formation of the line of "patriarchs" that keep the tradition grounded. It guides us in understanding the vigorous debates that Chinese Pure Land Buddhism evoked and delves into the rich apologetic literature that it produced in its own defense. Drawing upon a wealth of previously unexamined primary source materials, as well as modern texts by contemporary Chinese Pure Land masters, the author provides lucid translations of resources previously unavailable in English. He also shares his lifetime of experience in this field, enlivening the narrative with personal anecdotes of his visits to sites of Pure Land practice in China and Taiwan.The straightforward and nontechnical prose makes this book a standby resource for anyone interested in pursuing research in this lively, sophisticated, and still-evolving religious tradition. Scholars-including undergraduates-specializing in East Asian Buddhism, as well as those interested in Buddhism or Chinese religion and history in general will find this book invaluable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; t